Functions are reusable blocks of code that perform specific tasks.

**Function Definition:**
```cpp
return_type function_name(parameters) {
  // Function body
  return value;
}
```

**Example Function:**
```cpp
int add(int a, int b) {
  return a + b;
}

int main() {
  int result = add(5, 3);
  cout << "Sum: " << result << endl; // Sum: 8
  return 0;
}
```

**Void Function (No Return):**
```cpp
void greet(string name) {
  cout << "Hello, " << name << "!" << endl;
}

int main() {
  greet("Alice"); // Hello, Alice!
  return 0;
}
```

**Default Parameters:**
```cpp
int power(int base, int exponent = 2) {
  int result = 1;
  for (int i = 0; i < exponent; i++) {
    result *= base;
  }
  return result;
}

power(3);    // 9 (3^2)
power(3, 3); // 27 (3^3)
```

C++ allows multiple functions with the same name but different parameters.
```cpp
int add(int a, int b) {
  return a + b;
}

double add(double a, double b) {
  return a + b;
}

int main() {
  cout << add(5, 3) << endl;       // 8 (int version)
  cout << add(5.5, 3.2) << endl;   // 8.7 (double version)
  return 0;
}
```

**Rules:**
- Same function name
- Different parameter list (type, number, or order)
- Return type alone is not enough for overloading

Arrays store multiple values of the same type in contiguous memory.

**Declaring Arrays:**
```cpp
int numbers[5];              // Array of 5 integers
int scores[] = {90, 85, 95}; // Size determined by initializer
int ages[3] = {25, 30, 35};  // Array of 3 integers
```

**Accessing Elements:**
```cpp
int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

cout << arr[0] << endl; // 10 (first element)
cout << arr[4] << endl; // 50 (last element)
arr[2] = 100;           // Modify third element
```

**Array Size:**
```cpp
int arr[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
int size = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]); // 5
```

**Looping Through Arrays:**
```cpp
int numbers[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  cout << numbers[i] << " ";
}

// Range-based for loop (C++11)
for (int num : numbers) {
  cout << num << " ";
}
```

Arrays can have multiple dimensions for storing complex data.

**2D Arrays:**
```cpp
int matrix[3][3] = {
  {1, 2, 3},
  {4, 5, 6},
  {7, 8, 9}
};
```

**Accessing 2D Arrays:**
```cpp
cout << matrix[0][0] << endl; // 1
cout << matrix[1][2] << endl; // 6
```

**Looping Through 2D Arrays:**
```cppnfor (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
    cout << matrix[i][j] << " ";
  }
  cout << endl;
}
```

**3D Arrays:**
```cpp
int cube[2][2][2] = {
  {{1, 2}, {3, 4}},
  {{5, 6}, {7, 8}}
};
```

Arrays can be passed to functions for processing.

**Passing Array to Function:**
```cpp
void printArray(int arr[], int size) {
  for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
    cout << arr[i] << " ";
  }
  cout << endl;
}

int main() {
  int numbers[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
  printArray(numbers, 5);
  return 0;
}
```

**Modifying Array in Function:**
```cpp
void doubleArray(int arr[], int size) {
  for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
    arr[i] *= 2;
  }
}

int main() {
  int numbers[3] = {1, 2, 3};
  doubleArray(numbers, 3);
  // numbers is now {2, 4, 6}
  return 0;
}
```

**Note:** Arrays are passed by reference in C++, so modifications affect the original array.
